Why AGPL-3.0?

Younionize is open source: anyone may use, study, modify, and contribute to it.
The AGPL-3.0 adds one specific protection on top of the GPL: if someone runs a
modified version of Younionize as a hosted service that users interact with over
a network, they must publish their modifications under the same license.

In practical terms, this means:

  - Contributors and self-hosters: nothing to worry about. Use it, fork it,
    run it on your own servers, modify it for your own needs.
  - Companies that want to host a competing version of Younionize: you may do
    so, but your changes must also be released under AGPL-3.0 — you cannot
    take the code, improve it privately, and offer the improved product as
    a closed-source SaaS.

The AGPL is OSI-approved and is used by projects such as Mastodon, Nextcloud,
Plausible, and Grafana (originally) for the same reason: open source by intent,
with one specific guard against the SaaS-loophole free rider problem.
